{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c31e42cb-ff20-46ff-8298-b4b7140e53bc","content":"This is a **TUnit** project using MTP (Microsoft.Testing.Platform). TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` for filtering, not VSTest `--filter`.\n\nThe class is `SmsNotificationTests` in namespace `Contoso.Notifications.Tests`. The command is:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe treenode filter path format is `/Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test`, so `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` matches any assembly and namespace, the specific class, and all tests within it. The `--` separates `dotnet test` args from MTP args.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"04097264-dfaa-4c74-915f-565ea8496da9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit, the filter syntax is different from VSTest. TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` for filtering tests.\n\nTo filter by class name in TUnit, the treenode filter syntax is:\n```\n/**/*[*SmsNotificationTests*]/*/*\n```\n\nOr using `--filter` with the class:\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nWait, actually TUnit uses MTP by default. Let me check the project — it has `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` which confirms it's using MTP runner.\n\n\nFor TUnit with MTP, I need to pass the treenode filter through the MTP arguments using `--` separator. The command would be `dotnet test -- --treenode-filter` with the class filter pattern, or I could use `dotnet run` directly since it's an executable project.\n\nThe treenode filter follows the path structure `/Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test`, so to target just the `SmsNotificationTests` class, I'd use a pattern like `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` to match any assembly and namespace, then the specific class, then any test method within it.","outputTokens":552,"requestId":"4C16:1E6FAE:83C4AA:A35883:6A013156"},"id":"3a070cc8-5eb5-4e7f-8ace-a84b7431653e","timesta